{{Orphan|date=April 2016}}
[[File:Fred P. Evans.png|thumb|Fred P. Evans]] '''Fred P. Evans''' (born 1862) was a British spiritualist [[Mediumship|medium]].
He was born in [[Liverpool]] on 9 June 1862. His great grandfather was the Welsh social reformer [[Robert Owen]]. As a young man, Evans worked as a [[sailor]] and claimed to have experienced strange [[psychic]]al events.<ref>Owen, J. J. (1893). ''Psychography: Marvelous Manifestations of Psychic Power Given Through the Mediumship of Fred P. Evans, Known as the "Independent Slate-Writer"''. San Francisco, Hicks-Judd Company.</ref> In 1884 he moved to [[San Francisco]] where he gave séances to the public. Evans was an early proponent of slate-writing mediumship.<ref name="Melton 2013">[[J. Gordon Melton|Melton, J. Gordon]]. (2013). ''The Encyclopedia of Religious Phenomena''. Visible Ink Press. pp. 308-309. {{ISBN|978-1578592098}}</ref>
British biologist [[Alfred Russel Wallace]] who attended a séance with Evans in 1887 was convinced the slate-writing phenomena was genuine evidence for [[Spiritualism|spirit communication]] and reported that there were five different coloured messages.<ref>[[Alfred Russel Wallace|Wallace, Alfred Russel]]. (1908). [https://archive.org/stream/myliferecordofev00wall#page/352/mode/2up ''My Life: A Record of Events and Opinions''] London: Chapman & Hall. pp. 352-354</ref>
Slate-writing was popular in the late-nineteenth century but was discredited as fraudulent after investigations from [[Magic (illusion)|magicians]] and [[Parapsychology|psychical researchers]].<ref name="Melton 2013"/> In 1898, the magician [[Chung Ling Soo]] revealed the fraudulent slate-writing methods that Evans, [[Henry Slade]] and others had utilized.<ref>[[Chung Ling Soo|Soo, Chung Ling]]. (1898). [https://archive.org/details/spiritslatewriti00sooc ''Spirit Slate Writing and Kindred Phenomena'']. Munn & Company.</ref>
