'''John (Jack) Cristopher Coleman''' (died 20 April 1971) was a respected [[Irish people|Irish]] [[geographer]], [[archaeologist]], [[speleologist]] and [[mountaineer]]. He devoted much of his life to the study of the caves of Ireland, the product of which were his many contributions to scientific journals in Ireland and the United Kingdom, his founding of the [[Speleological Union of Ireland|Speleological Society of Ireland]] and the publishing of his book, ''The Caves of Ireland''.

His dedication to the exploration of Irish caves and highly respected articles published both nationally and abroad were pivotal in boosting the study of speleology in Ireland during the mid to late 20th century, earning him the affectionate title of the "father of Irish caving".<ref name=is20 />

==Life and caving exploits==
Coleman was born in [[Cork (city)|Cork]], Ireland and worked for [[Bord Fáilte]] from 1945,<ref name=reyfadeer-obit>{{cite journal| title=Obituary: Jack Coleman| editor1-last=Shiels| editor1-first=W.| editor2-last=Jones| editor2-first=G. Ll.| journal=The Reyfadeer: The Reyfad Group Journal| volume=1| year=1973| page=36}}</ref> having trained as a geographer in [[University College Cork|Cork University]]. He began caving in 1932,<ref name=coleman-ubssireland>{{cite journal| title=The society in Ireland| last=Coleman| first=J. C.| journal=[[Proceedings of the University of Bristol Spelæological Society]]| volume=12| issue=1| year=1969| pages=75–82| url=http://www.ubss.org.uk/resources/proceedings/vol12/UBSS_Proc_12_1_75-82.pdf| format=PDF| accessdate=26 January 2013}}</ref> initially exploring caves within cycling distance of his home in Cork City such as [[Carrigtwohill Caves]]<ref>{{cite journal| title=Exploration of a new cave discovered at Carrigtwohill, Co. Cork| last=Coleman| first=J. C.| journal=Journal of the Cork Historical and Archaeological Society| series=2| volume=XXXIX| year=1934| pages=76–78}}</ref> and Ovens Caves. In 1940 Coleman met [[Portlaoise]] [[Polymer chemistry|textile chemist]] N. J. Dunnington, who joined him in explorations of caves in South Cork. In July 1941 the pair cycled heavily laden bicycles to [[County Clare]] to investigate [[Pollnagollum]],<ref name=coleman-ubssireland /> and over the ensuing years undertook a systematic exploration of the cave system. In 1944 the [[Royal Irish Academy]] published an article on the cave system by Coleman and Dunnington,<ref>{{cite journal| title=The Poulnagollum cave, Co. Clare| last1=Coleman| first1=J. C.| last2=Dunnington| first2=N. J.| journal=[[Proceedings of the Royal Irish Academy]]| volume=L| issue=B|date=October 1944| issn=0791-7945| pages=105–132}}</ref> which received widespread praise from the scientific community and attracted a new wave of speleologists to [[the Burren]].<ref name=coleman-ubssireland />

Coleman was the first speleologist to identify scalloping as an indicator of the direction of water flow in a cave. His findings, made between 1946 and 1949, were published by the [[University of Bristol Spelæological Society]] (UBSS).<ref>{{cite journal| title=An indicator of water-flow in caves| last=Coleman| first=J. C.| journal=[[Proceedings of the University of Bristol Spelæological Society]]| volume=6| issue=1| year=1949| pages=57–67| url=http://www.ubss.org.uk/resources/proceedings/vol6/UBSS_Proc_6_1_57-67.pdf| format=PDF| accessdate=26 January 2013}}</ref> Coleman would later cite the relationship that he built with the society over the following years to be a major stimulus in continuing his work on Irish caves, and ultimately in completing his book on the subject. By the 1960s he had been made Honorary Life Member of the UBSS.<ref name=coleman-ubssireland />

Throughout the 1950s Coleman carried out much scientific fieldwork in areas such as Counties [[County Sligo|Sligo]], [[County Monaghan|Monaghan]] and [[County Kerry|Kerry]],<ref name=coleman-ubssireland /><ref>{{cite journal| title=Caves near Carrickmacross, County Monaghan| last=Coleman| first=J. C.| journal=[[Irish geography]]| volume=II| issue=4| year=1952| pages=180–183}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal| title=Caves in the Tralee district| last=Coleman| first=J. C.| journal=Journal of the Cork Historical and Archaeological Society| series=2| volume=LV| year=1950| pages=25–30}}</ref> and the [[Cong, County Mayo|Cong]] region,<ref>{{cite journal| title=Caves in the Cong area of Galway and Mayo| last=Coleman| first=J. C.| journal=[[Irish geography]]| volume=III| issue=2| year=1955| pages=94–106}}</ref> which would pave the way for further discoveries by local and visiting speleologists.

In 1964 Coleman founded the [[Speleological Union of Ireland|Speleological Society of Ireland]], the first representative body for cavers in Ireland. He was also the first editor of the Society's journal ''[[Irish Speleology]]''. Coleman published his work widely in a number of publications. His articles included work on [[Dunmore Cave]], Carrigtwohill Caves and Pollnagollum,<ref>{{cite journal| title=Dunmore Cave, Co. Kilkenny| last1=Dunnington| first1=N. J.| last2=Coleman| first2=J. C.| journal=[[Proceedings of the Royal Irish Academy]]| volume=53B| year=1950| pages=15–24| issn=0791-7945| jstor=20490874}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal| title=Excavation at Carrigtwohill Caves, Co. Cork| last1=Coleman| first1=J. C.| last2=Stelfox| first2=A.W.| journal=[[Irish Naturalists' Journal]]| volume=8| issue=8| date=Sep 1945| pages=299–302| issn=0021-1311| jstor=25533361}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal| title=The Pollnagollum Cave, Co. Clare, Éire| last1=Coleman| first1=J. C.| last2=Dunnington| first2=N. J.| journal=[[Journal of the British Speleological Association]]| volume=1| issue=4| year=1948| pages=100–120}}</ref> but it was not until 1965 that his seminal work, ''The Caves of Ireland'', was published.<ref name=CoI-review>{{cite journal| last=Holgate| first=H. F.| year=1966| title=Review: 'The caves of Ireland' by J.C. Coleman| journal=[[Irish Naturalists' Journal]]| volume=15| issn=0021-1311| page=156}}</ref> Originally written by Coleman as his [[Master of Arts|MA]] thesis at [[University College Cork|Cork University]],<ref name=reyfadeer-obit /> the book was the first and currently only publication to comprehensively list and describe cave sites throughout Ireland.<ref name=CoI-review />

Coleman was also a prominent member of the [[Irish Mountaineering Club]] and was president of the club from 1950–1953.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.irishmountaineeringclub.org/past-presidents/ |title=Past Presidents: Irish Mountaineering Club presidents through the years |publisher=Irish Mountaineering Club |accessdate=2014-08-25}}</ref>

Coleman was killed in a car accident on 20 April 1971, at the age of 57. He was survived by his wife, son and three daughters.<ref name=is20>{{cite journal| title=Seeing the light of day: the archives of Jack Coleman and Dónal Gilhoys| last=Dowd| first=Marion| journal=[[Irish Speleology]]| issue=20| date=October 2013| publisher=[[Speleological Union of Ireland]]| issn=0332-4907| pages=34–41}}</ref><ref name=ubss12-3>{{cite journal| title=Obituary – J.C. Coleman, M.A.| last=Tratman| first=E. K.| journal=[[Proceedings of the University of Bristol Spelæological Society]]| volume=12| issue=3| year=1971| pages=231–232| url=http://www.ubss.org.uk/resources/proceedings/vol12/UBSS_Proc_12_3_231-232.pdf| accessdate=25 August 2014}}</ref>

