'''Jean Meeus''' (born 12 December 1928) is a Belgian [[meteorologist]] and amateur [[astronomer]] specializing in [[celestial mechanics]], [[spherical astronomy]], and mathematical astronomy.<ref name="MPC-Asteroid-Meeus">
{{Cite web | url = https://www.minorplanetcenter.net/db_search/show_object?object_id=2213 | title = (2213) Meeus | website = [[Minor Planet Center]] | publisher = [[International Astronomical Union]] | access-date = 25 May 2018 }}
</ref><ref name="MAM"> {{Cite book | title = Mathematical Astronomy Morsels | last = Meeus | first = Jean | publisher = Willmann-Bell | year = 1997 | isbn = 0-943396-51-4 | location = Richmond, Virginia | page = (Author Biography) }} </ref>
Meeus studied mathematics at the [[Catholic University of Leuven (1834–1968)|University of Leuven]] in [[Belgium]], where he received the Degree of [[Licentiate (degree)|Licentiate]] in 1953. From then until his retirement in 1993, he was a [[meteorologist]] at [[Brussels Airport]].<ref name="MAM" />
== Awards and honors ==
In 1986, he won the [[Amateur Achievement Award of the Astronomical Society of the Pacific]].<ref name="Amateur Achievement Award">
{{Cite journal | last = Wolff | first = S. | author-link = Sidney C. Wolff | last2 = Fraknoi | first2 = A. | author-link2 = Andrew Fraknoi | date = June 1986 | title = Jean Meeus received the Amateur Achievement Award of the Astronomical Society of the Pacific. | journal = Mercury | publisher = [[Astronomical Society of the Pacific]] | volume = 15 | issue = 5 | pages = 142–3 | bibcode = 1986Mercu..15R.142W }} </ref> The [[main belt]] asteroid [[2213 Meeus]] was named after him by the [[International Astronomical Union]] in 1981 for his contributions to the field.<ref name="MPC-Asteroid-Meeus" /><ref name="MAM" />
